block subSubTitle
	h1
		b Length of a curve
block subSubContent
	h3
		b Introduction
	p We have a curve from \(a\) to \(b\) in \(\mathbf R^n\).
	p \(f:[a,b]\rightarrow \mathbf R^n\)
	p We divide this into \(n\) segments.
	p The \(i\)th cut is at:
	p \(t_i=a+\dfrac{i}{n}(b-a)\)
	p So the first cut is at:
	p \(t_0=a\)
	p \(t_n=b\)
	p The distance between two sequential cuts is:
	p \(||f(t_i)-f(t_{i-1}||\)
	p The sum of all these differences is:
	p \(L=\sum_{i=1}^n ||f(t_{i})-f(t_{i-1})||\)
	p The limit is:
	p \(L=\lim_{n\rightarrow \infty }\sum_{i=1}^n ||f(t_{i})-f(t_{i-1})||\)
	h3
		b Method 1
	p \(L=\lim_{n\rightarrow \infty }\sum_{i=1}^n ||f(t_{i})-f(t_{i-1})||\)
	p \(L=\lim_{n\rightarrow \infty }\sum_{i=1}^n ||\dfrac{f(t_{i})-f(t_{i-1})}{\Delta t}||\Delta t\)
	p \(L=\lim_{n\rightarrow \infty }\sum_{i=1}^n ||f'(t)||\Delta t\)
	p \(L=\int_a^b ||f'(t)||dt\)
	p 
	h3
		b Method 2
	p \(L=\lim_{n\rightarrow \infty }\sum_{i=1}^n ||f(t_{i})-f(t_{i-1})||\)
	p \(L=\lim_{n\rightarrow \infty }\sum_{i=1}^n \sqrt {(f(t_{i})-f(t_{i-1}))^*M(f(t_{i})-f(t_{i-1}))}\)
	p \(L=\int_a^b \sqrt {(dt)^TM(dt)}\)

